docs.abstract: Fresh off a frantic election cycle, the former Fetterman campaign social media producer  — and dedicated Swiftie — takes time to shake it off.
docs.snippet: Fresh off a frantic election cycle, the former Fetterman campaign social media producer  — and dedicated Swiftie — takes time to shake it off.
docs.lead_paragraph: Newt Gingrich was not happy. It was the night of Dec. 6, minutes before the U.S. Senate race in Georgia was called for Raphael Warnock, and over on the Fox News show “Hannity,” the finger-pointing for Herschel Walker’s imminent loss had begun. One major culprit: TikTok.

headline.print_headline: Getting the Message Out From the Inside

docs.abstract: The developing nations in Africa have yet to experience any enduring gains from Silicon Valley’s financial speculation.
docs.snippet: The developing nations in Africa have yet to experience any enduring gains from Silicon Valley’s financial speculation.
docs.lead_paragraph: Jack Dorsey, a billionaire co-founder of Twitter, is a major investor on the African continent. Meta’s C.E.O., Mark Zuckerberg, has heavily invested in tech start-ups in Nigeria. Earlier this year, The Economist declared that Africa is the only region in the world “not suffering from a slowdown in venture capital.”

headline.main: Africa Is Waiting for What You Promised, Mark Zuckerberg and Jack Dorsey
headline.print_headline: Africa Is Waiting for What Big Tech Promised

docs.abstract: As some Black families celebrate Kwanzaa this week, we asked children to share their impressions of this nonreligious holiday honoring African American culture.
docs.snippet: As some Black families celebrate Kwanzaa this week, we asked children to share their impressions of this nonreligious holiday honoring African American culture.
docs.lead_paragraph: “Kugichagulia!” said  Parker Johnson, 5, of Pasadena, Calif., giggling as he pronounced the Swahili word three times in rapid succession. One of the seven principles of Kwanzaa, the word means self-determination and it is Parker’s favorite in the lexicon of the weeklong, nonreligious holiday that celebrates African American culture.

headline.main: Day 27: What Are Kids Saying About Kwanzaa?

docs.abstract: The statue, scheduled to be erected next fall in Roanoke, Va., is part of a local project to recognize Black history in community spaces.
docs.snippet: The statue, scheduled to be erected next fall in Roanoke, Va., is part of a local project to recognize Black history in community spaces.
docs.lead_paragraph: A life-size bronze statue of Henrietta Lacks, the woman whose cancer cells were taken without her consent and were used for research that ushered medical discoveries and treatments, will be erected in her hometown, Roanoke, Va., next year in a plaza previously named after the Confederate general Robert E. Lee.

headline.main: A Statue of Henrietta Lacks Will Replace a Monument to Robert E. Lee

docs.abstract: While the country isn’t in the same league as global producers, a large variety of beautiful stones are found within its borders.
docs.snippet: While the country isn’t in the same league as global producers, a large variety of beautiful stones are found within its borders.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the 1970s, when Jaymus Perry was growing up on the Navajo Nation reservation near Buell Park, Ariz., he and his siblings used to fill coffee cans with the raw peridots and chrome pyrope garnets that they found and sold the gems to local trading posts for spending money.

docs.abstract: The scene on the tarmac with Brittney Griner and Viktor Bout didn’t just show a prisoner trade. It told the story of where two rival countries had landed decades after the Cold War.
docs.snippet: The scene on the tarmac with Brittney Griner and Viktor Bout didn’t just show a prisoner trade. It told the story of where two rival countries had landed decades after the Cold War.
docs.lead_paragraph: As I grew up in the 1980s, my image of a prisoner swap was the old one from the Cold War: Two men, agents caught by the enemy, standing on opposite ends of a bridge in Berlin. The American and Soviet officials who surround them have done this all before. Tensely, slowly, the men cross the bridge — there’s always a glance at the middle — and then agents go home.

headline.main: When a Prisoner Swap Is a Rorschach-Test
